Blue Plate is without a doubt my favorite restaurant in San Francisco. I've suspected this to be the case for many years, but last night's experience cinched the title. At Blue Plate one can always find interesting menu and wine list options. With regard to their awesome wine list, there are well priced both accesible and obscure grapes to choose from, great atmosphere, great vibe and friendly service. Talking on the menu, the chef is adventurous without being outlandish and the flavor combinations always seem to work. The drunken macaroni and cheese and grilled romaine salad are always winners, but the fresh and seasonal menu always throws forth some interesting takes on comfort food. Last night the Pork shoulder with figs, polenta was outstanding. Meric, Logan, Michelle and I drank 2 bottles of an Italian grape I hadn't heard of called LaGrain and thoroughly enjoyed them. Desert is not something you should ever pass up while dining at at Blue Plate as Val the pastry chef (and double dutchess hero!) kicks some asses. When the weather is nice the back patio is awesome, but the cozy open kitchen set up makes dining inside a 100% charming and fun experience. I've been sold for years, this place is awesome. Love The Blue Plate, yes indeedy.

This is a really cute spot in the outer mission. It's sort of out of the way for me, but it was well worth the trip. They have a really nice heated garden area in the back, where we had a drink while waiting for our table. There isn't a ton of room in the restaurant, and the kitchen is right smack dab in the middle of the restaurant, set up sort of like a diner - but much much nicer. I think we ordered just about every appetizer they had on the menu, but the beet salad was most memorable. Since we had so many appetizers, I split the pasta dish with a friend, and then to top it all off, we tried the mint chocolate ice cream sundae - yum! Cute spot with a funky dark sort of decor with a really creative menu. I'd like to try a few more of the entree items and will be back.

First, the food here is great. It's a little more expensive than front porch (just around the corner), but the difference is noticeable and well worth it. Since the food at front porch is pretty good, blue plate's clear superiority puts it on the fast track for five stars. As such, I heartily recommend you go there, and don't bother reading the rest of my review, because it is merely serving a therapeutic value to me. However. Blue plate loses just one star primarily for the poor service and secondarily for the cramped atmosphere. I'm not normally one to heavily criticize the wait staff. I know they aren't there to serve at my beck and call, rather they are there to earn money to pay rent and other such expenses. That being said, I do expect some level of service, and my expectations do increase as the price of the meal increases. At blue plate, you can expect to spend in the range of $100-150 for dinner for two. Since I almost invariably give a 20% tip, that means the server is getting 20-30 dollars for their troubles. Since our server didn't yell at me or blurt out racist epithets, I gave her the standard 20%, but I don't feel like she really earned it. She was not helpful when asked about the menu, was in a terrible rush the whole time, took part in the restaurant-wide conspiracy to get us off the table so that the line of people waiting could be seated, and even pushed the menu I was reading out of her way to put water on the table without saying excuse me. Standing alone, these offenses would not be a big deal, but together they bothered me. Remember again, this meal cost well over 100 dollars. Oh, and she was suddenly so sweet when she set down the check to be paid. I hate that. The atmosphere at blue plate is also pretty cramped, but I guess that's just part of the urban eating experience. If you are like me, and you don't like to be seated so close to people that you can easily take part in their dinner conversations, then blue plate might not be for you. However, drinking a few $1 cans of Olympia beer as soon as you get there seems to lessen the discomfort caused by the close proximity of other diners. All-in-all, blue plate is a great restaurant, and their status is only lessened by factors that don't really upset the dining experience. So, go there!

Update: I now am a carnivore and this place get's 5 stars for creating classic American dishes that exude originality and a commitment to local ingredients. If I was a carnivore, Blue Plate would get five stars. The cuisine is haute gourmet home style comfort food. A new menu everyday. Every dish I tried was incredible. I started off with the grilled anchovies with pesto sauce and the halibut cheeks with fava beans and linguine. For a main course I had the grilled salmon served medium rare. For dessert, a strawberry rhubarb pie with buttermilk icecream. The best I've tried. Scott ordered the chocolate espresso cake which was unbelievably decadent and traversed the entire chocolate landscape before landing in lake espresso. From cocoa to dark chocolate to an unsweetened bakers chocolate all in a tiny rich cake. The food and atmosphere are neither pretentious nor underwhelming. My table may have been slightly more boisterous than preferred for our neighbors hoping for a romantic dinner. Highly recommend BP and especially for all the carnivores or homesick midwesterners looking for a slice of meatloaf and potatoes.

Food is just okay. Nothing really spectacular and do I dare say bland?! Cute place, but a bit cramped for my taste. Parking is difficult also. They don't offer valet and the parking lot is several blocks away. All and all not really worth making the trek to come to this place especially with the pricey entrees. We came on a Friday night and it was busy. I wish our waiter was more attentive.

Highly recommend BP and especially for all the carnivores or homesick midwesterners looking for a slice of meatloaf and potatoes.
